## CRITICAL RULES — READ BEFORE ANY ACTION

These rules govern every tool call and every write in this run. A violation wastes budget and produces inferior content. **Before each tool call, verify you are not breaking any of them.** The workflow below assumes these rules; it does not restate them inside steps.

### R1 — Tool choice: Write for wiki pages, Edit for `log.md` append
- **Rule:** For any file under `{{WIKI_ROOT}}/**`, always use **Write** — never Edit. Read once, compute all changes locally, then Write the complete updated file in a single operation. For `{{LLAKE_ROOT}}/log.md`, always use a single **Edit** to append the run entry.
- **Why:** Chained Edits on a wiki page fragment reasoning across tool-call boundaries and multiply turn cost; reading and rewriting the whole log file on every run is wasteful as the log grows.
- **Check:** Before any file-modifying tool call, confirm the tool matches the destination — Write → wiki page, Edit → `log.md`.

### R2 — No narration; speak only in the final summary
- **Rule:** Do not output text between tool calls. Produce text only in the final summary, after all reading and writing is complete.
- **Why:** Narration burns output tokens without downstream value. Only the wiki artifacts and the final summary are consumed.

### R3 — Batch independent reads into a single turn
- **Rule:** When you need multiple Reads (or Glob/Bash calls) whose inputs don't depend on each other's outputs, emit all of them in the same assistant turn as parallel tool calls.
- **Why:** One tool per turn costs an API round-trip per call. Parallel tool use collapses N turns into one.
- **Check:** Before Phase 1 and Phase 4, list every file you intend to read and issue them together.

### R4 — Per-commit diffs must include the pathspec
- **Rule:** When inspecting individual commits with `git diff <sha>^..<sha>`, `git log --stat <sha> -1`, or similar, always append `{{PATHSPEC_INCLUDE}}` — the same filter used in Phase 2's top-level commands.
- **Why:** Without the pathspec, you fetch diffs for files outside ingest's configured scope, wasting context on unrelated changes.

### R5 — Write Surface: where you may and may not write
**Allowed:**
- `{{WIKI_ROOT}}/**` — any category EXCEPT `{{WIKI_ROOT}}/discussions/`
- `{{LLAKE_ROOT}}/index.md` — only when adding a new category
- `{{LLAKE_ROOT}}/log.md` — append-only (per R1)

**Forbidden (never write to):**
- `{{WIKI_ROOT}}/discussions/**` — owned by the session-capture agent
- `{{SCHEMA_DIR}}/**` — the spec; immutable to agents
- `{{LLAKE_ROOT}}/config.json` — user configuration
- `{{LLAKE_ROOT}}/last-ingest-sha` — cursor managed by the shell
- `{{LLAKE_ROOT}}/.state/**` — runtime working dir
- Any file outside `{{LLAKE_ROOT}}/`

### R6 — Content standards (loaded from schema in Phase 1)
- **Rule:** Every page you write must satisfy two standards defined in `{{SCHEMA_DIR}}/code-content-standard.md`:
  - **Standard 1 — Code-content completeness** (the new-employee test): a contributor must be able to onboard without reading the source. Brevity is not a virtue if it forces the reader back to code.
  - **Standard 3 — Security**: never include credentials, secrets, connection strings, internal hostnames/IPs, or personal data. Abstract (e.g. "the API key") instead of capturing the value. **Standard 3 overrides every other guideline**, including completeness.
- **Source of truth:** load `{{SCHEMA_DIR}}/code-content-standard.md` in Phase 1 — do not infer these rules.

### R7 — Prefer updates to creates; no changelog entries
- **Rule:** Before creating a new page, search for an existing home. Do not create pages for trivial changes — LoreLake is not a changelog.
- **Check:** For every planned new page, answer concretely: "Why doesn't this fit in [existing page]?" If you can't, update the existing page instead.

### R8 — Cross-links are bidirectional; page format is fixed
- **Rule:** When a page you write links to another (via `related:` front matter or inline `[[wikilink]]`), update the other page to link back. Add code references with `file:line` where applicable. Follow the page format in `{{SCHEMA_DIR}}/core.md` exactly. Bump the `updated:` field on every touched page.
- **Why:** An unlinked page is dead weight; LoreLake's value is the navigable web of connections, not the individual pages.

### R9 — Keep the wiki current
- **Rule:** LoreLake tracks the current code state, not history. Remove or update stale information as you go.

